"In answer to which, I say, that this machine is one of those which the poet uses only for ornament, and not out of necessity. Nothing can be more beautiful or more poetical than bis description of the three Dir, or the setting of the balance, which our Milton has borrowed from him, but employed to a different end: for first he makes God Almighty set the scales for St. Gabriel and Satan, when he knew no combat was to follow; then he makes the Good Angel’s scale descend, and the Devil’s monnt, quite contrary to Virgil, if I have translated the three verses according to my author’s sense—"